<dt> Prototype papier : "Prototyping for Tiny Fingers" </dt>
<dd> En lien avec [la semaine jeu video](http://communaute.amontourdeprogrammer.fr/t/sixieme-semaine-jeu-video-multi-joueur-en-javascript/204), une ressource que je partage souvent avec mes étudiants :

http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~./bam/uicourse/630spring04/rettigOnPrototyping.pdf

You should take a look the linked PDF, Prototyping for Tiny Fingers, because it's a classic paper on low fidelity prototyping and why it's an useful practice.

It also embodies the idea that our sketches / prototypes / drafts are useful only if we use them for testing. Any version you build should be enough, but not more, that what you need to learn and (in)validate your work hypothesis.

(This is also the basis of the Lean Startup movement that advocate building Minimum Viable Products)

Most of the times testing means user testing, as in "testing my prototypes with a least one real user". You will find guidelines for user testing in the attached article PDF.

(but in short: give a task to your users, ask them to talk aloud when doing it, let them do the task without interrupting them or giving them instructions).

PS: Following is the full text of Prototyping for Tiny Fingers (without illustrations) as an alternative to the PDF.

Prototyping for Tiny Fingers

Rettig, Marc

Communications of the ACM (April 1994)

Abstract: The technique of building user interface prototypes on paper and testing them with real users is called low-fidelity (lo-fi)prototyping. Lo-fi prototyping is a simple and effective tool that has failed to come into general use in the software community. Paper prototyping is potentially a breakthrough idea for organizations that have never tried it, since it allows developers to demonstrate the behavior of an interface very early in development, and test designs with real users. If quality is partially a function of the number of iterations and refinements a design undergoes before it enters the market, lo-fi prototyping is a technique that can dramatically increase quality. It is fast, it brings results early in development, and it allows a team to try far more ideas then they could with high-fidelity prototypes. The steps for building a lo-fi prototype include: 1. Assemble a kit. 2. Set a deadline. 3. Construct models, not illustrations. Steps for preparing for and conducting a test of the prototype are also discussed.

INTRODUCTION

Consider this familiar situation: a development team spends weeks designing an interface. They draw sketches on the board, discuss each point in detail, and finally specify a design. The design is either coded into the application language or simulated with a software prototyping tool. The result is finally shown to users for approval, in a session that generates scores of comments on subjects ranging from the basic metaphor to the choice of background color. The team just barely has time to incorporate these comments into a revised design before committing their work to production.

Now consider a different situation, one I have witnessed first-hand over the past few months: a development team spends weeks designing an interface. During the first few days, they construct a paper prototype of their initial thinking about all aspects of the design, and test it with typical representatives of the user community. One of them “plays computer,” moving components of the paper interface around on the table in response to the users’ actions. The others observe and take notes. After the tests they take a week to distill lessons from their observations, redesign the interface, and retest with several new users. This process continues until, at the end of the time allotted for interface design, the team has revised their design four times and tested it with many typical users.

This technique--building prototypes on paper and testing them with real users--is called low-fidelity prototyping or “lo-fi” for short. The value of prototyping is widely recognized, but as the first situation exemplifies, that value is not always gained in practice. If that has been your experience, you might want to try lo-fi prototyping which requires little more in the way of implementation skills than the ones you learned in kindergarten.

The idea of lo-fi prototyping (a.k.a. “paper prototypes”) has been around a long time. So long, in fact, that more than one person in the CHI community expressed surprise when I said I was planning to write a column on the subject. But I see this as a wonderfully simple and effective tool that has somehow failed to come into general use in the software community. I say this based on the success of the teams I’ve watched over the past several months together with the fact that this is the first commercial project where I’ve seen paperprototypes employed.

Paper prototyping is potentially a breakthrough idea for organizations that have never tried it, since it allows you to demonstrate the behavior of an interface very early in development, and test designs with real users. If quality is partially a function of the number of iterations and refinements a design undergoes before it hits the street, lo-fi prototyping is a technique that can dramatically increase quality. It is fast, it brings results early in development (when it is relatively cheap to make changes), and allows a team to try far more ideas than they could with high-fidelity prototypes. Lo-fi prototyping helps you apply Fudd’s first law of creativity: “To get a good idea, get lots of ideas.”

THE PROBLEMS WITH HI-F1

For years developers have used everything from demo-builders to multimedia tools to high-level languages to build prototypes. Lo-fi proponents call these “hi-fi prototypes.”
They have their place: selling an idea, testing look-and-feel, detailed proof-of-concept, testing changes to an existing system, and so forth. I’m not suggesting we should stop building them. But they also have problems.

HI-F1 PROTOTYPES TAKE TOO LONG TO BUILD AND CHANGE. Even with high-level tools, a fully functional prototype can take weeks to create. I have seen teams build a complete working lo-fi prototype in four hours. ?he goal is to get through as many iterations as you can during the design phase, because each iteration means improvement. If testing flushes out problems with the basic metaphor or control structure in a design, changing the prototype can again take weeks. This is what Debbie Hix and Rex Hartson, researchers and faculty members at Virginia Tech, call the “Software developer’s dilemma.” You can’t evaluate an interaction design until after it is built, but after building, changes to the design are difficult. Paper prototypes, on the other hand, are extremely fast to develop and the technique is very easy to learn. It is the fastest of the so-called rapid prototyping techniques. To make a broad generalization, interface designers spend 95% of their time thinking about the design and only 5% thinking about the mechanics of the tool. Software-based tools, no matter how well executed, reverse this ratio.

REVIEWERS AND TESTERS TEND TO COMMENT ON “FIT AND FINISH”
ISSUES. You are trying to get feedback on the big things: the flow of the conversation, the general layout of the controls, the terminology, the expressiveness and power of the basic metaphor. With a slick software prototype, you are just as likely to hear criticisms about your choice of fonts, color combinations, and button

sizes. On the back side of the same coin, developers easily become obsessed with the prettiness-power of a good tool, and spend their hours choosing colors instead of coming up with new ideas. In contrast, the hand-made appearance of a paper or acetate prototypeforces users to think about content rather than appearance.

DEVELOPERS RESIST CHANGES. They are attached to their work because it was so hard to implement. Spend enough time crafting something and you are likely to fall in love with it. Knowing this, team members may feel reluctant to suggest that their colleague should make drastic changes to the lovely looking, weeks-in-the- making software prototype. They would be less hesitant to suggest redrawing a sketch that took an hour to create.

A PROTOTYPE IN SOFTWARE CAN SET EXPECTATIONS THAT WILL BE HARD TO CHANGE. Prototyping tools let you do wonderful things in a (relatively)
short time. You can make something that looks like a finished product, fooling testers and even management into thinking how far you are along. If it tests well, you may wind up spending time on “reverse damage control,” handling questions about your sudden lack of progress.

A SINGLE BUG IN A HI-F1 PROTOTYPE CAN BRING A TEST TO A COMPLETE HALT. To test effectively, your prototype needs to be complete and robust enough for someone to try to do something useful with it. Even with the coolest of high-level tools, building aprototype is still essentially a programming exercise--and we all know how hard it can be to get all the bugs out of a program. On the other hand, I often see teams correcting “bugs” in a paper prototype while the test is in progress.

A TROJAN MEME

The spread of lo-fi design through my current project started with a visit from Jared Spool (with User Interface Engineering in Andover, Mass.). He and his associate presented the basic ideas, then put us to work in four teams to design and build a prototype of an automated menu for a fast food restaurant. For three hours we discussed, designed, sketched and glued, then ran the results in a face-off competition with “real users” and a “real task.” That is, we brought people in from elsewhere in the building and told them, “you have $4.92. Order as much food as you can.” The designs were measured by how quickly and efficiently people could use the interfaces without coaching from the designers. Between tests, each team had a few minutes to refine their interface.

We were all impressed with the results of the exercise. In about six hours we had learned the technique, designed an interface and built a model of it, conducted tests, and measurably improved the original design. That was four months ago, and now we have scores of people working on lo-fi designs, refining them through repeated tests with actual users. Interface sketches are lying all over the place, scans are put on the network for peer review, and terms like “affordance” and “mental model” are common parlance.

I call this a “Trojan meme” instead of just a “selfish meme” because it did more than reproduce itself through the department. (A meme is an idea--the mental equivalent of a gene, and selfish ones try to replicate themselves in as many minds as possible.) As it spread, it served as a vehicle for spreading a general appreciation of the value of usability design: developers saw first-hand the difference in people’s reactions to successive refinements in their designs. Within days of designing an interface, they saw exactly how their work was perceived by people just like those who will eventually be using their product. The value of two important laws of interaction design was memorably demonstrated: “Know Your User,” and “You Aren’t Your User.”

Testing for iterative refinement is known in the interface design community as “formative evaluation,” meaning you are evaluating your design while it is still in its formative stages. resting is used as a kind of natural selection for ideas, helping your design evolve toward a form that will survive in the wilds of the user community. This is in contrast to
“summary evaluation,” which is done once after the product is complete. With summary evaluation you find out how well you did, but you find out too late to make substantial changes.

Lo-fi prototyping works because it effectively educates developers to have a concern for usability and formative evaluation, and because it maximizes the number of times you get to refine your design before you must commit to code. To make the most of these advantages, the prototyping effort needs to be carefully planned and followed by adequate testing and evaluation. (It also helps to have someone who can enthusiastically champion the idea.) Hix and Hartson have an excellent chapter on formative evaluation in their book, Developing User Interfaces. If you plan to adopt any of these techniques, I recommend you read their book.

The rest of this is drawn from our experience over dozens of designs and scores of tests, notes from Jared Spool’s workshop, and Hix and Hartson’s book.

BUILDING A LO-FI

1. ASSEMBLE A KIT.

In this decadent age of too many computers and too few paint brushes, it might be hard to get all the materials you need by rummaging through the supply closet in the copy room.
Make a trip to the office supply store, or better yet, the art supply store, and buy enough school supplies to excite the creative impulses of your team. Here’s a shopping list:

White, unlined, heavy paper that is bigger than letter size (11 by 17 inches is nice), and heavy enough to endure the rigors of repeated testing and revision.

Hundreds of 5-by-&inch cards. These come in handy as construction material, and later you’ll use them by the score for note taking during tests.

Various adhesives. Tape: clear, colored, double-backed, pin striping tape, whatever.
Glue sticks, and most importantly, Post-It glue--a stick of the kind of glue that’s on

PROTOTYPE

the back of those sticky yellow notes. Rolls of white correction tape are great for button labels and hurriedly written field contents.

Various markers--colored pens and pencils, highlighters, fine and thick markers, pastels.

Lots of sticky note pads of various sizes and colors.

Acetate sheets--the kind you use to make overhead presentations. Hix and Hartson swear by these as the primary construction material for lo-fi interfaces.

See what you find in the architecture section. They have sheets of rub on texture, for example, which could give you an instant shading pattern.

Scissors, X-acto knives, straight edges, Band-Aids.

Just like kindergartners, lo-fi designers sometimes find inspiration in the materials at hand. So go ahead--buy that package of colored construction paper. The worst that can happen is you won’t use it. Eventually your team will develop their own construction methods, and settle on a list of essentials for their lo-fi construction kit.

2. SET A DEADLINE.

There is a terrific temptation to think long and hard about each aspect of the interface before you commit anything to paper. How should you arrange the menus? What should be in a dialog box, what should be in menus, and what should be in a tool palette When you are faced with a blank sheet of paper, these kinds of decisions crowd your thoughts all at once. “Wait,” you think, “we haven’t thought about this enough!”

That’s exactly the point: no matter how hard you think about it, you aren’t going to start getting it right until you put something in front of actual users and start refining your idea based on their experience with your design. So set a deadline. Obligate yourself so you are forced to take a preliminary crack at every important aspect of your problem. If you know four users are coming tomorrow expecting to work with your prototype, you’ll have far less trouble with fixations on minor details. You will make some decision, any decision, about the most important aspects of your design, and get them down on paper for testing. Quality comes through iterative refinement. Get the big things right during lo- fi, and the little things will follow in future iterations.

3. CONSTRUCT MODELS, NOT ILLUSTRATIONS.

As you build, make something that will be easy to control for the person playing computer. Draw a genetic frame (a window frame, if you are building a windowing interface) on a big piece of heavy stock. Then make each region of the screen on a different piece of card stock. Anything that moves, changes appearance, or comes and goes, should probably be on its own piece of stock. Remember you’ll eventually be playing computer, and you’ll need to have a ready response for almost anything the user might do while trying to complete the test tasks. Make what you need to simulate menus

dropping down, dialogs popping up, selection highlights, and so forth (see Figure 1).
(Figure 1 omitted)

Making a working model of an interface challenges you to be creative. Need to represent a long scrolling list? How about cutting slots in the dialog box and running adding machine paper through it? Want a working tabbed notebook metaphor? Cut up cards or file folders to make them the right size, draw the interface components below the tabs, and stack up the results so the tabs stagger the way you want. Use colored acetate to represent selection highlighting. Tape clear acetate handles to things that move around a lot, so you can handle them easily without obstructing the user’s view.

The photocopier can be a lo-fi architect’s best friend. Make yourself lots of blank windows, dialogs, buttons and fields, in several sizes. Get a fresh start by painting white-out over mistakes, then using the copier to produce a new unsoiled version.

You’ll find that different people excel at different aspects of lo-fi construction: design, inventing ingenious paper implementations of widgets, producing large amounts of data, or rendering artistic and attractive designs. Exploit these talents and divide the labor accordingly.

Construct a first version completely by hand. Sketch the widgets, hand-letter the labels.
Don’t even worry about using a straightedge at first. Just get the ideas down on paper.
Test small details on one another, or drag people in from the hall for quick tests of alternative solutions.

Of course, hand-drawn sketches, no matter how carefully done, may not be appropriate for some testing situations. For example, a customer may be willing to let you test your design with actual users. They may understand the transience of the prototype, but you still want to make a good impression. You want to look sharp.

Some of the teams on my project have made remarkably attractive paper interfaces using components created with drawing software, then printed on a laser printer. Some of them build up a familiar look with elements taken from screen captures. To facilitate this kind of thing, they set up a library of lo-fi widget images: blank buttons of all sizes, window and dialog frames, scroll bars, entry fields, and so on. People print these out, resize them on the photocopier, and make them part of their standard lo-fi kit. Or they resize them on the computer, add labels, and print out a custom part for their work in progress. This is an example of the kind of preparation that will help lo-fi prototyping become a normal part of your design process. Preparing a widget library, writing down guidelines, and taking time to train people will make everyone more enthusiastic and productive.

PREPARING FOR A TEST

However much care you take in building your prototype, the tests will be ineffective unless you prepare well for them. Be sure to attend to the following matters.

1. SELECT YOUR USERS.

Before you start designing, you should do enough user and task analysis to understand the people who will be using your software-their educational and training background, knowledge of computers, their familiarity with the domain, typical tasks involved in their job, and so on. Based on this study, you can look for pools of potential testers for your prototype. With a good user profile on hand, you can develop a questionnaire that will help to choose the best representative users from available candidates.

It would seem reasonable to arrange it so the people testing your prototype are the same people who will be using the final product. But bona fide members of the user community may be hard to corral for the time it takes to run a test, and using them may not be the best idea in the long run. Be sensitive to the political climate. People may feel threatened by the intrusion of a new system into their work (perhaps justifiably!), or there may be a competitive situation that makes your employer reluctant to expose new ideas outside the walls of your building.

Since you are looking for appropriate knowledge and skills, not job titles, you can often get by with “surrogate users”--people who fit the same profile as your actual clients, but free from whatever association that prevents you from testing with the clients themselves.
I’ve heard of all kinds of tricks for attracting people to the test. Spool says he’s done everything from running ads in the newspaper to recruiting university students to contacting local user groups. Anything to avoid using actual customers, employees, or friends and family. (The latter may be accessible, but there are a lot of things about sharing ties in the same social web that can conspire to damage a usability test. For example, testers who know you or the project may skew the results by trying hard to please you or do what they think you expect them to do.)

Finally, remember that no two people are the same, and your product’s users may be a diverse group. Try to recruit testers that represent the whole range of characteristics in your target audience. Our practice has been to conduct at least one round of testing in our office with surrogates, then go to the field for testing with the most typical end users we can find.

2. PREPARE TEST SCENARIOS.

Write a set of scenarios, preferably drawn from task analysis, describing the product during use in a typical work situation. Design yourprototype to support a few of these scenarios, narrowing the scope of your efforts to a reasonably small set of functions, but broad enough to allow meaningful tests.

If possible, ask someone to review the scenarios and sample data and tell you whether they look realistic. In our experience, people find a lo-fi interface more engaging--more realistic--if it shows data that looks familiar and we ask them to perform realistic tasks.
This helps draw them into the “let’s pretend you’re really using a computer at your job” world, which leads to better tests. On the other hand, unrealistic scenarios and data can severely damage the credibility of your design.

3. PRACTICE.

Just as a bug in a software prototype can ruin a test session, so can a bug in a lo-fi prototype. That bug could be a missing component, a misunderstanding on the part of the person playing “computer,” or even excessive hesitation and confusion because the team is unfamiliar with how to conduct a rest. So to avoid embarrassment, conduct several dry runs before you test with people from outside your team. Each team member should be comfortable with his or her role, and you need to make sure you have the supplies and equipment needed to gather good information.

CONDUCTING A TEST

We find it takes four people to get the most out of a test session (see Figure 2), and that their activities fall into four essential roles: (Figure 2 omitted)

GREETER. Much the same as the usher in a church, the greeter welcomes users and tries to put them at ease. We have some forms we ask people to fill out--an experience profile, for example--a job the greeter handles while other team members are setting up for the test.

FACILITATOR. Once the test is set up, the facilitator takes the lead, and is the only team member who is allowed to speak freely during the test. Facilitating means three things: giving the user instructions, encouraging the user to express his or her thoughts during the test, and making sure everything gets done on time. This is a difficult enough job that the facilitator should not be expected to take notes during a session.

COMPUTER. One team member acts as the “computer.” He or she knows the application logic thoroughly, and sustains the illusion that the paper prototype behaves similar to a real computer (with an unusually slow response time). A pointing finger serves as a cursor, and expressions like, “I type half-silvered bicuspidors’ in that field” substitute for keyboard entry. If the user touches a control, the computer arranges the prototype to simulate the response, taking care not to explain anything other than the behavior of the interface.

OBSERVERS. The rest of the team members quietly take notes on 5-by-8-inch index cards, writing one observation per card. If they think of a recommended solution, they write it on the same card that records the problem.

Since all of these roles can be exhausting, we rotate them among the team when we conduct more than one session a day (and we very often schedule four sessions in a day).

Typical test sessions usually last a little over an hour, and go through three phases:
getting ready, conducting the test, and debriefing. We begin with greetings, introductions, refreshments and general ice-breaking, trying our very best to assure people that the test is confidential, the results will remain anonymous, and their supervisor won’t hear a word about whether or not they “got it.” People often say things like, “Am I flunking the test?
Am I getting it right?” To which we answer, “Don’t worry, the question is whether or not we are flunking. The interface is on trial, not you. If you fail to understand something or can’t complete one of the tasks, that’s a sign of trouble with the design, not a lack of intelligence on your part.”

While this is going on, someone positions a video camera (we tape all the sessions) so it points down over the user’s shoulder to look at the interface and the hands moving over it.
No one’s face ever appears on tape.

During the test, the facilitator hands written tasks to the user one at a time. These must be very clear and detailed. As the person works on each task, he facilitator tries to elicit the user’s thoughts without influencing his or her choices. “What are you thinking right now?” “What questions are on your mind?” “Are you confused about what you’re seeing!”

While this is going on, the rest of the team members observe and take notes, and may occasionally interject a question. But they must never laugh, gape, say “a-ha,” nudge one another, or otherwise display their reaction to what’s happening to their careful design.
This kind of thing can intimidate or humiliate users, ruining the relationship and spoiling the test. It can be terribly difficult to keep still while the user spends 10 minutes using all the wrong controls for all the wrong reasons. You will feel a compelling urge to explain the design to your users. Don’t give in.

When the hour is over, we spend a lo-minute debriefing session asking questions, gathering impressions, and expressing our thanks.

EVALUATING RESULTS

Lo-fi or hi-fi, prototyping is worthless unless information is gathered and the product is refined based on your findings. As I wrote earlier, Hix and Hartson nicely cover the details of gathering and analyzing test data. We spend quite a bit of time (at least a day per iteration) sorting and prioritizing the note cards we wrote during the test sessions. Our method involves arranging the paper prototype on a big table, then piling the note cards next to its relevant interface component. Then team members divide the labor of going through the piles to summarize and prioritize the problems.

These sorted piles inform a written report on findings from the test, and form the agenda of a meeting to discuss recommended changes to the design. The team works through the piles and agrees on suggested changes, which are written on Post-It notes and affixed directly to the relevant part of the paper prototype. Constructing the revised prototype becomes a process of taking each component, and following the recommendations that were stuck to it.

TRY IT

Hix, who for years has been teaching courses and workshops in interface design, says that people consistently enter the first lo-fi exercise with skepticism. After trying it they invariably say something to the extent of, “I can’t believe how much we learned from this!” If this column is the first place you have heard about the lo-fi technique, one danger is that you will set aside this magazine with just enough skepticism that, however much interest I’ve managed to create, you will fail to actually try it.

Having seen other skeptics converted, I’m confident in recommending this technique. If you already have a working high-fidelityprototype, it probably isn’t worth abandoning that course to switch to lo-fi. But if you are in the very early stages of design and exploring broad questions, or if you need to learn more now, lo-fi prototyping is just the tool to pick up.

RESOURCES

Brown, D. STUDIO: Structured User-Interface Design or Interaction Optimisation. New York, Prentice Hall, 1994.

Hix D. and Hartson, R. Developing User Interfaces: Ensuring Usability Through Product and Process. New York: Wiley & Sons, 1993.

Nielsen, J. Finding usability problems through heuristic evaluation. In Proceedings of SIGCHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems. ACM, New York, 1992, pp. 373-380.

Rudd, J. and Isenee, S. Twenty-two tips for a happier, healthier prototype. Interac. 1, 1
(Jan. 1994), 35-40.

Marc Rettig is a senior architect at Andersen Consulting in Chicago. He can be reached at 76703.1037compuserve.com, or 100 S.
Wacker, Chicago, IL, 60606. </dd>

<dt> Septième semaine - Objets vivants avec Arduino (basé sur C et C++) </dt>
<dd> LUNDI

**matin**
Démo arduino avec Jonathan et Julien.
On peut faire des choses très ludiques et interactives en connectant des objets et différents éléments électroniques comme des capteurs, leds, moteurs etc...
On programme à partir du logiciel Arduino, la carte Arduino est connectée à l'ordinateur avec un câble micro USB.

Le petit moteur utilisé comporte 3 fils : 
- masse (ground)
- volte
- celui du milieu qui permet la modulation (signal)

Il existe pleins d'exemples dans Arduino.
L'exemple utilisé pour la démo était dans Servo : 
https://www.arduino.cc/en/Tutorial/Sweep

il y a une limitation en octet et donc en nombre de caractères. Pour optimiser un programme, on peut par exemple utiliser des constantes à la place de variables.

Un pin représente une broche. Sur Arduino on a des broches numérotées de 0 à 13

Il existe différents types d’interrupteurs, dont le tilt switch.

on peut demander à Arduino de nous renvoyer des infos :
Serial.println(« coucou »)

**après-midi**
Répartitions en groupes sur différents projets. Avec Marine et Cécile, nous avons réussi à afficher "Hello World" sur un petit écran led connecté avec Arduino. Il y avait beaucoup de fils à connecter et je n'ai pas bien compris à quoi ils correspondaient. Nous n'arrivions pas à afficher la phrase, puis grâce àl 'aide de Jonathan et Julien, nous avons pu mettre les bonnes résistances, permettant d'afficher le bon contraste.
Je n'ai pas bien compris comment fonctionnent les résistances.

<img src="/uploads/default/original/1X/5d5e3d8011de7b3472fd59314f6998ae747746eb.JPG" width="260"><img src="/uploads/default/original/1X/c07fb3bd48544a39ae60413f8f4165085a43616c.JPG" width="260">


_
MARDI
Forum avec Étienne et Jonathan

_Le microprocesseur_
Il communique avec de la mémoire ROM et RAM, reçoit et envoie des info par l'intermédiaire d'interfaces (clavier, écran, micro)
L'ensemble : microprocesseur + ROM + RAM + Interface = Microcontroller 
Arduino est un microcontroller, il existe ussi des SOC (system on ship) comme Raspberry pie. Je n'ai pas bien retenu ce qu'était un SOC, mais j'ai retenu que le Raspberry était plus puissant, notamment en terme de mémoire.
Un microprocesseur peut être multi-coeur (bi-coeur, triple, quadri...), comme la plupart des ordinateurs...

_L'interrupteur_
Il y a un niveau haut ou bas. Le MC ne peut pas observer un état haut ou bas, mais prélève une toute petite partie du courant afin de voir dans quel sens il va (+ ou -). Le - a un effet "aspirateur". Donc il y a en quelques sorte toujours du courant, un coup dans un sens (+), un coup dans l'autre qui aspire pour bloquer le passage.
Merci Jonathan pour la métaphore du moulin qui m'a bien aidée à comprendre le principe :)

<img src="/uploads/default/original/1X/21beaa623914b613f3354d0345112108f0c51a8b.jpg" width="374" height="500">


_La résistance_
phrase d'accroche : "Rien ne peut rivaliser avec le fil"
permet d'obtenir le bon niveau de tension (ce qui explique que nous avions eu besoin d'avoir le bon réglage afin d'afficher le bon contraste sur l'écran LCD)
Dans la carte Arduino, il y a une micro résistance interne que l'on peut utiliser en la programmant afin de lui demander de se connecter avec : 
`pinMode (2, INPUT_PULLUP)`

Il faut mettre une résistance à côté d'un interrupteur pour avoir toujours un courant UP ou DOWN (1 ou 0), soit on ajoute une résistance extérieure ou on branche la résistance interne d'Arduino.


_Le potentiomètre_
Pour régler et adapter la tension. 

<img src="/uploads/default/original/1X/aea15a358a3d7291592168f04542ddcb6a1a644f.jpg" width="550">


Et enfin découverte de Makey makey (un kit utilisant la techno Arduino), qui semble très amusant à manipuler pour expérimenter des choses interactives et ludiques comme une touch banane pour faire de la musique ou des manettes de jeu en pâte à modeler etc...

<dt> Création d'évenements de découverte du Code et de ses métiers </dt>
<dd> Dans le cadre de à mon tour de programmer, nous avons lancé une nouvelle série d'événements dont le but est de faire découvrir le code et son univers. Nous avons appelé ces événements **"Hello World !"**

Ces événements s'adressent 
* aux participantes 
* aux personnes qui n'auront pas pu être retenues
* aux personnes qui sont en cours d'apprentissage (peu importe le niveau acquis)
* aux personnes qui se posent des questions

Pour organiser ces événements, nous nous appuyons sur notre réseaux pour trouver des lieux qui nous accueillent et sur nos membres pour venir partager leurs expérience, leurs réussites ou encore leurs connaissances.

Ces événements auront lieu à différents moments de la journée (matin, midi ou soirée) afin de permettre à tous de participer.

L'objectif est de ne pas dépasser les 2h30 et de permettre des moments d'échange libre (entre 20 et 40 min) après l’événement. 

Ces événements doivent aussi proposer des boissons et petites choses à grignoter afin de rendre l’atmosphère plus accueillante. </dd>

<dt> Troisième semaine - Serveur HTTP/Proxy sans utiliser de libraire ni de framework (Go) </dt>
<dd> Avec ce thème, nous allons toucher une des bases d'internet : le protocole [HTTP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypertext_Transfer_Protocol). 

Il existe aujourd'hui beaucoup de serveur HTTP, mais certains sont plus connu que d'autres : le [serveur Apache](http://httpd.apache.org/) est un des plus répandu, l'est-il toujours ? Il a donné naissance à la [Fondation Apache](http://apache.org/) qui gère depuis 1999 un portefeuille de projets open source de plus en plus large ! [Nginx](http://nginx.org/) est un "petit nouveau" qui est de plus en plus utilisé ces dernières années. Et nous avons le grand classique pour les personnes utilisant des serveurs Windows (assez rare dans le monde du web tout de même)  [IIS](https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/1c64b5ab-d155-4654-b3d1-4f265749e3fc) de chez Microsoft.

## Objectifs pédagogique

- Comprendre HTTP
- Notions réseau
- Système de type
- Compilation
- Travailler ensemble
- Architecture logiciel


## Pour se préparer

Le langage que nous utiliserons est [go](https://golang.org/). C'est un langage compilé (à l'inverse de la plupart de vos langages de prédilection actuel qui sont interprétés), et typé (un peu comme nous avons vu dans le code source de Processing, écrit en Java).

Je vous demande donc, en plus d'une partie des prérequis comme git et github de la [Première semaine](http://communaute.amontourdeprogrammer.fr/t/premiere-semaine-faire-un-bot-en-javascript/27), il vous faut...
- [télécharger Go](https://golang.org/dl/)
- l'[installer Go](https://golang.org/doc/install) sur vos machine
- suivre le tuto [How I start Go](http://howistart.org/posts/go/1/)

ps: le site [how I start](http://howistart.org/) propose des tutoriels sur les premiers pas dans divers langages, c'est plutôt bien fait et intéressant.

<dt> Neuvième semaine - Ecrire un interpréteur dans le langage de votre choix </dt>
<dd> **Monday**

A compiler takes code in and sends other code out. 
An interpreter takes code in and runs it. 
Let’s play with compilers.

_Stack Overflow_
When a program starts running, a section of memory - called the Stack - is set aside for the program. So that when a function call is executed, we remember where we’re at and what we got (=> cf. Jonathan’s recipe analogy: remember where you’re at before each cooking task so you don’t start all over again).
This memory space is limited, and it may very well overflow if you’re not careful, hence “stack overflow”.

_Stack optimisation_
To avoid this, some compilers recognise when they don’t need to overwhelm the stack. For example, when the subroutine called is the last instruction (the tail call) of the function, instead of allocating a new stack frame they simply return the result of the call (=> “tail call optimisation”, often used for recursive functions).

_Compiler examples_
A Java compiler generates instructions to a Java virtual machine’s microprocessor;
A Go compiler generates instructions directly to a physical machine’s microprocessor.

_A compiler’s many jobs_
- write code for one instruction (native or user-defined)
- chain instructions

**Wednesday**

_Language libraries_
3 levels of libraries: 
- core library: given by default, 
- standard library: available but must be loaded, 
- external libraries

_Ruby interpreters_
jruby > written in Java
rubinius > written mostly in Ruby

_Machine processes_
`ps | grep node` to see node processes for example, 
`process` in node console to see one process </dd>

* Sprint Backlog - is a forecast by the dev team about what functionality will be in the next increment and the work needed to deliver that functionality into a "done" increment.

<dt> L'esprit du mentorat Ladies of code </dt>
<dd> Channel relatif au mentorat Ladies of code.

**L'esprit du mentorat**

Il s'agit d'un mentorat basé sur l'humain et un partage d'expérience, débutant en Mars et se terminant en Novembre (modulo les vacances de chacune).

Les apprenantes du programme (12) sont de fausses-débutantes et ont déjà quelques notions de code. Le but du programme est qu'elle puisse trouver un job en tant que développeuse.

Je vois le mentorat comme un levier parfait pour les aider à s'intégrer pleinement dans la communauté dev, à comprendre la culture dév et à mieux appréhender leur futur métier.

Quand j'ai débuté dans l'IT, j'ai eu la chance de rencontrer une femme super impliquée dans la communauté, qui m'a présenté à plein de monde, m'a initié aux meetups, m'a rassurée sur les entretiens tech et parlé des boîtes sympas ! Ca m'a beaucoup inspiré et aidé à construire le chemin que je voulais. Elle a été un rôle modèle, et c'est dans cet esprit que j'imagine ce mentorat.

Un point important selon moi est de donner des clés / points d'entrées à ces femmes qui débutent et n'ont pas encore leurs marques dans la communauté dev. Bien sûr c'est à chacune de trouver comment partager sa passion pour la tech et le code, et de s'arranger avec sa mentorée (call / email / café / rencontres meetup...). </dd>

<dd> Monday 

When selecting colors for the cables in arduino (to connect to a device), try using he same colors that the device has, or else it might no work.

Ways to save memory life: create constants so it will not use dinamic memory overload the RAM. 

Arduino ha a _microcontroller_ which is a self-contained system. It has peripherals, memory and a processor and an input output system. It is used for example in cellphones, cars or household. It must not be mistaken for a _microprocessor_, which incorporates the functions of a computer's central processing unit (CPU).

There' a magic thing called tilt switch that has a little ball inside (there's one called mercury switch that has Mercury on the inside), and it can determinate if the object has changed position when the ball moves. 

Arduino can send information to the computer.



Tuesday

PinMode configures the specified pin as input or output. It 2 parameters

pin - the # of he pin you're using

mode - can be
* INPUT - This pins make extremely small demands on the circuit, so it takes very little current to change that pin from one estate to another. If there's nothing connected it will pick electrical noise from where it can.
* OUTPUT - It is in a low-impedance state. It gives a little current through that pin. Because it has an output, it is necessary to use resistances in order to avoid a short circuit.
* INPUT_PULLUP - The Atmega chip jas 20k pull-up resistors, INPUT_PULLUP is to be able to use them. Inverts the behavior of the INPUT mode, where High means the sensor is off, and Low means the sensor is on. 

A pull-up resistor is a resistor connected between a signal conductor and a positive power voltage to ensure that the signal will be a valid logic level if external devices are disconnected.

Wednesday

Today we worked on tests! We chose the Potter Kata, and did the development in Go :3 </dd>

<dt> Bienvenue sur «À mon tour de programmer !» ! </dt>
<dd> Merci d'avoir rejoint «À mon tour de programmer !» et bienvenue !

For a few quick tips on getting started as a new user, [check out this blog post](http://blog.discourse.org/2016/12/discourse-new-user-tips-and-tricks/).

As you participate here, we’ll get to know you, and temporary new user limitations will be lifted. Over time you’ll gain [trust levels](https://meta.discourse.org/t/what-do-user-trust-levels-do/4924) that include special abilities to help us manage our community together.


Nous croyons au [comportement communautaire civilisé](http://communaute.amontourdeprogrammer.fr/guidelines) en tous temps.

Amusez-vous bien !

(Si, en tant que nouvel utilisateur, vous avez besoin de communiquer avec un [responsable](http://communaute.amontourdeprogrammer.fr/about), répondez simplement à ce message.) </dd>
<dt> Spectacle Impromptu scientifique le 6/7 </dt>
<dd> https://lieu.maifsocialclub.fr/programmation/scientifique

Les impromptus sont volontairement interdisciplinaires, avec un goût particulier pour les mathématiques et les neurosciences. Ils sont toujours suivis d’un temps de discussion et d’échange avec le public.

Le lieu dans le Marais est plutôt sympa </dd>

<dt> Perspective 2018 «À mon tour de programmer !» </dt>
<dd> Notre bilan à l'approche de la fin de formation :

- Embauches de nos apprenantes : 
    - @loreenRH est en CDI chez [Docker](https://www.docker.com/)
    - @Anna-Livia est  en mission chez [Etalab](http://www.etalab.gouv.fr/) de juin 2017 à décembre 2017, 
    - @Lisa est en CDI chez [Dimelo](http://www.dimelo.com)
    - @eli_j est en CDI chez [MakeMusic](https://www.makemusic.com/)
    - @EliPamp et @SarahB travaillent chez [MagikMakers](https://www.magicmakers.fr/)
    - @Cecile_B est maintenu chez [Artips](http://www.artips.fr/) où elle travaille sur des scripts en python et des apps en Angular

- Entreprises rencontrées dans le cadre de la formation : 20 structures, 23 CTOs, CEOs, lead devs, devs. 

- Succès pédagogiques sur le collaboratif et l'alternance des semaines, permettant un ancrage des savoirs et un "devenir équipière".

- Activité croissante de la plate-forme d'échanges, ouvertes aussi aux professionnelles et débutantes ne suivant pas encore la formation.

- Impact positif sur la communauté de développeuses parisienne avec +250 Ladies of Code, +3 organisatrices et une augmentation de la fréquence des évènements en 2017.


Les perspectives et améliorations que nous mettons en place en 2018.

- Certification niveau II (bac+4) préparée et proposée systématiquement à toutes apprenantes. 

- Prise en charge de grandes débutantes grâce à un parcours continu incluant une préparation télé-présentielle.

- Former et intégrer 30 développeuses professionnelles, soit deux fois et demi la cohorte 2017 : Doublement des sessions, augmentation à 15 apprenantes par session. 

- Baisse significative du coût par apprenante (-54%) sans baisse de la qualité pédagogique.

- Regroupement des activités dans un lieu rassembleur, au service des acteurs de l’écosystème qui en manque cruellement : préfiguration d'une «Cantine du Code», ou «Maison du Code». </dd>

<dd> Salut à toutes,

Pour celles que Rub ne repousse pas, et qui sont partantes pour faire un peu de JavaScript aussi parfois, je vous conseil de vous inscrire sur le slack de Paris.rb (http://parisrb-slack-invite.herokuapp.com/) dans le chan #job, il y a souvent des offres qui pourraient vous intéresser. 

Il y a aussi leur site https://www.rubyparis.org/ sur lequel on retrouve des offres.

La communauté a tendance à séparer Front et Back (comme beaucoup), mais vous pouvez peut-être rencontrer les gens et voir comment les équipes sont organisé pour de vrai, et proposer ce que vous avez envie de faire :slight_smile:

A plus tard.
-- Yannick. </dd>
<dt> Deuxième semaine - Œuvre Numérique en Processing (Java) </dt>
<dd> *Monday*

_Handy in Processing_
- the Tweak mode
- Trigonometry (hello sinus my old friend[:musical_note: ](https://youtu.be/4zLfCnGVeL4)) 
- Anti-aliasing
- Playing with time: the default frameRate is 60fps. It is considered good practice not to toy with the frameRate but rather vary the increments within the drawing loop and/or use functions such as millis())

_Other_
- Processing is based on Java and as such is a static typed language. 
- GitHub gives you the option to ignore standard files and to add a license when creating a new repo
- Conclusion of the morning show: one can do a LOT of things by tweaking very FEW lines of code.

**Tuesday**

- In Processing, global variables must be declared outside the `setup` function, but they can be initialized within it.
- You can call/manipulate JSON files with Processing without adding any external libraries 🕶

**Wednesday**

_General_
- Vocabulary: a method signature. eg in Java: `public void myFunction(parameter1, …)`
- In many programming languages, you can use tools to generate documentation from comments in source code (Javadoc for Java, RDoc for Ruby etc.)
- Console refresher: `grep -r “keyword”`

_Java/Processing_ 
- Arrays in Java are of fixed size that is specified when they are declared. (Sigh) => use ArrayLists instead
- Using a `<frame>` could be handy to include a Processing sketch in a webpage
- html/js note: you can get the script currently being executed with `document.currentScript`, read its `textContent`… and [display](http://ut7.fr/jardins/artpop.html) it with Processing! 

_Good code reading habits_
- Dissociate literals; keywords inherent to the language (cf learnXinYminutes); and user-defined keywords
- Reflect on first gut reaction in front of the code and afterthoughts after getting into the code

_Git/GitHub_
- To delete a remote branch:  `git push origin :remote_branch_to_delete`
- Git refresher: `git commit --author=“mygithubpseudo <myemail@address.com>” ...` 
- There is a handy search option within a repo in GitHub 

Oh, and: 
There is a spoiler tag [plugin]([plugin](https://github.com/discourse/discourse-spoiler-alert) ) for Discourse!

**Friday**

- useful to set specific objectives at short coding intervals to avoid digressions (even for more open "artistic" projects)
- thou shalt remember 60 times per second that the `draw()` function in Processing loops itself 60 times per second (default frame rate)
- discovery of the submarine cable map while reading the journal entries

**Questions**

- GitHub: when to use fetch rather than pull, renaming a repo
- On the Web: how to integrate/interact with Processing on a webpage
- In Processing: how to create dynamic textboxes, how to zoom in on canvas elements
- Why does Java separate arrays of fixed and dynamic size?
 
_Methods_
- How to work on projects with more active contributors (how to deal with merge conflicts, when to pull/how often, understanding the risks of git rebase etc.)
- How to work on projects with a wider scope (how to breakdown the project into user stories, how to manage our progress with agile tools etc.)
- How to use TDD effectively
- How to contribute to an OS project </dd>
<dt> Maneki Neko, quand l'AI amplifie l'altruisme </dt>
<dd> **_Maneki Neko_** (par Bruce Sterling, 1999) est une nouvelle de science-fiction qui raconte la transformation par les réseaux sociaux d'un japon post-money où le don piloté par le réseau lui même, intelligent, devient la norme d'échange.
Mais pour les représentants des anciens mécanismes (ici, le fisc américain !) ce nouveau système d'échange est compris comme une vaste fraude, une activité criminelle. 

Datant de 1999, cette nouvelle a été écrite avant l'émergence des réseaux sociaux actuels et des outils collaboratifs de masse. En la lisant, on a le sentiment qu'ils sont encore bien loin d'avoir joué leur rôle social au maximum de leur potentiel. Elle raconte aussi l'écart émotionnel, l'incompréhension entre deux mondes, cette incompréhension que l'on retrouve entre les utilisateurs enthousiastes des nouveaux outils d'échanges et d'organisation (p2p, plateformes, blockchain, wiki…) et ceux qui n'y voit que la destruction et la barbarie (par exemple, oui, Wikipedia a été et est encore présenté comme la destruction barbare du savoir…)

Version originale en anglais : 
http://www.lightspeedmagazine.com/fiction/maneki-neko/

(suite à une discussion avec @Anna-Livia :slight_smile:) </dd>

<dt> Travailler dans les "Digital Humanities" (humanités numériques) </dt>
<dd> Il existe des métiers au croisement de l'informatique et des 'humanités' (sciences sociales/humaine, lettres, histoire). Mais ces métiers sont peu connus à la fois de Pôle Emploi et des responsables d'écoles ou de formations.

**Voici des ressources pour les développeuses qui souhaiteraient travailler dans cette mouvance des humanités numériques.**

https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humanit%C3%A9s_num%C3%A9riques

La liste 'DH' (pour Digital Humanities) est la liste française où se retrouvent tous les acteurs qui se reconnaissent de ce croisement.
Y sont publiés de nombreuses d'offres d'emploi, car tout le milieu a le réflexe de poster sur cette liste. Comme toujours les annnoces ne sont pas à ne prendre au pied de la lettre, et il faut rencontrer les labos ou institutions même si ils semblent demander "plus" que votre profil.
https://groupes.renater.fr/sympa/info/dh

Les "concours" externes du CNRS – c'est à dire le recrutement en externe sur des postes de fonctionnaires sont ouverts depuis le 6 juin. Il peut être intéressant de regarder :
http://www.dgdr.cnrs.fr/drhita/concoursita/consulter/resultats/consulter.htm

**À ce sujet (les postes du CNRS) :**
Le référentiel des postes de la recherche et de l'enseignement supérieur est intéressant, car on se rend compte qu'il y a hors de la Branche d'Activité Professionnelle de l'informatique (la BAP E) des profils de poste comme le profil ci-dessous, qui peut très bien recouvrir des activités de développement d'outils autour de données, de création de flux de traitement de données de la recherche (texte, photos, 3D, etc.). Il est classé en BAP F soit la _"Branche d'Activité Professionnelle Culture, Communication, Production et diffusion des savoirs_" 

F2A43 - Chargé-e du traitement des données scientifiques 
https://data.enseignementsup-recherche.gouv.fr/pages/fiche_emploi_type_referens_iii_itrf/?refine.referens_id=F2A43#top

Le référentiel est juste un outil pour repérer comment sont classés et offert les postes, car de fait et en pratique de nombreuses personnes au CNRS sont à cheval sur plusieurs profils de poste.

**Pour mieux comprendre le milieu :**

L'association francophone des humanités numériques/digitales
Intéressant pour repérer qui sont les membres et leurs projets. http://www.humanisti.ca/

Un grand campus sciences sociales est en préfiguration. L'équipe qui le monte est actuellement à la Maison des Sciences de l'Homme de Paris Nord https://www.campus-condorcet.fr/ </dd>

<dt> Huitième semaine - Participer à un projet Open Source </dt>
<dd> Le logiciel libre grignote, de plus en plus nous en utilisons, parfois sans le savoir. Une des choses magnifique que permet la distribution de logiciel sous une licence libre, c'est de pouvoir lire du code écrit par d'autres. <dd> **Monday**

_Ways to contribute to the open-source community_

- use open-source projects (e.g. Firefox, Linux, LibreOffice…)
- report an issue on an os project (but check if it’s already been reported before)
- solve one

_Back in the days_
Before GitHub (and its magic Fork functionality) was launched in 2008, to propose modifications to a project, you’d send an email to its maintainer in the form of a **patch** that (s)he can then apply to the project’s Git repo.
(You’d say: 'PTAL!', they’d end up saying: 'LGTM!’)
(¡ Every Git commit is a patch, hence the `git add -p`!)
(¡ GitHub is written in Ruby and Erlang!)

_Back in a repo's days_
When you rebase a branch on another branch, it rewrites your local history but not your remote’s history (cf `git glog`) => `push--force` to update your remote graph.  
Squashing options for interactive rebase: 
- default: squashes commits and asks you which message to keep
- `autosquash` option for fixups - to dig in! 

_Shell_
`.` is the same as `source`! </dd>

<dd> **Lundi**
Pour contribuer à un projet open source, il y a plusieurs façons :
signaler un bug, corriger un bug, ajouter un readme…

**Workflow**
- Forker le projet, puis cloner en local
- Ajouter ensuite un remote vers le projet d’origine (l’appeler upstream)
- on bosse en local puis on push sur notre repo distant
- on crée une pull request depuis l’interface de Github
- s’il y a des modifs faire les modifs en local puis repusher sur notre repo distant pour mettre à jour la pull request

Pour faire une nouvelle contribution, on supprime notre branche puis :
- on met à jour notre repo local depuis upstream 
- on met à jour notre repo distant
- on crée notre branche en local et on code :)

**Exports nodes**
Par défaut les objets ne sont pas disponibles d’un module à un autre, il faut les exporter.

objetJavascript {
 clé : valeur
}

    var toto = ‘Etienne’

--

    var a = require(‘./a.js’)
    console.log(a.toto_externe)
    //renvoie ==> toto

Si on veut juste exécuter et pas récupérer un objet exporter on peut faire require sans le mettre dans une variable :

on peut connecter son compte Github avce Travis CI, les miss à jous e font automatiquement

_Merge et rebase_

A partir d’un dernier commit d’un projet (par exemple : v3), on peut créer une branche pour apporter des modif (v4), puis ensuite merger sa branche sur le master. 
Mais parfois, entre temps, un nouveau commit peut avoir été fait sur le master (v5) et l’on peut alors   merger sa version avec la dernière, donc v4 + v5, ou bien faire un rebase, en raccodant sa branche sur la base du dernier commit du master (v4’).

Attention car en faisant un rebase, on peut perdre les commentaires de ses commit.

Après résolution d’un problème de conflit : 
	git rebase  - -continue
va rebaser tous les commit à la suite

Je vais revoir ces notions que je n’ai pas bien saisies :
squash
fixup
git rebase -i - -autosquash


2 / Node : Exports et require

On en a besoin car on ne peut pas appeler des objets d’un fichier js externe, c’ets en quelques sorte sécurisé, verrouillé. 

syntaxe : 
    module.exports = {
    toto_externe : toto ;
    	}
OU
`exports.toto_externe = toto ;`

Quand on met un require d’un fichier, Quand on exécute un fichier (b.js) dans lequel on a mis un require d’un autre fichier (a.js), b va exécuter a.
	
	var function_exporte_par_a = require(« ./a.js »);

On peut exporter des objets ou des fonctions. </dd>

<dt> Manifestation d'intérêt : devenir développeuse en 2018 avec «À mon tour de programmer !» </dt>
<dd> Vous souhaitez intégrer durablement les métiers du code (programmation et développement) et devenir développeuse ?

Le programme «À mon tour de programmer !» est conçu pour ​répondre​ ​aux​ ​besoins​ ​des​ ​femmes​ ​qui​ ​souhaitent​ ​devenir​ ​développeuses professionnelles.​ 

La particularité de la formation «À mon tour de programmer !» est de former les participantes pour qu'elles soient prêtes à intégrer des équipes de développement, à être des équipières. L'accent est donc mis sur la programmation comme une activité collaborative et d'équipe.

Répondez à l'appel à manifestation d'intérêt pour le programme : [Je suis intéressée par devenir développeuse en 2018 avec «À mon tour de programmer !»](https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1UUJMYSDIj8giXffzbQN5-c9Ddd010FUrfsTa4J-hGf8/edit)
Vous serez ainsi tenue au courant et parmis les premières averties du lancement des sessions.

Les grandes lignes du programme : 

- une formation aux piliers de la programmation

- du mentorat par des professionnel•le•s 

- un accompagnement au projet professionnel

- Une immersion dans les communautés des développeuses et développeurs

Le site donne plus de détails : http://amontourdeprogrammer.fr
Vous pouvez aussi parcourir les différentes catégories de la plateforme d'échange : http://communaute.amontourdeprogrammer.fr/ </dd>
<dt> Sixième semaine - Jeu vidéo multi joueur en JavaScript </dt>
<dd> Cette semaine, nous ferons un jeu, toutes ensemble, en JavaScript. En plus de la contrainte de langage, nous souhaitons faire un jeu multijoueurs : c'est quand même plus sympa de pouvoir jouer à plusieurs.

Pour avancer, il faudra trouver un équilibre entre élargir les possibilités du jeu et le rendre mieux fait.

## Objectifs pédagogique

* Apprendre à travailler à plusieurs sur un logiciel (synchronisation, intégration, organisation...)
* Programmation par évènement
* Accès concurrent

## Pour se préparer

L'idée étant de ne pas partir de zéro, nous vous proposons d'utiliser une librairie permettant de faciliter la construction de jeu. Jonathan suggère [Phaser.io](https://phaser.io/), mais peut-être que le groupe préfère ra utiliser un [autre moteur](https://github.com/showcases/javascript-game-engines). 

Je poste ce message un peu tard (samedi soir), si vous vous ennuyez demain, je vous invite à explorer un ou deux moteurs de jeux pour avoir des éléments pour choisir.


## Équipe

Pour continuer à explorer le travail en équipe, toutes les développeuses vont travailler sur le même projet cette semaine. Le jeu s'appelle [LunchBreak](https://github.com/amontourdeprogrammer/lunchBreak)


## Déroulé

- Lundi matin : Kata avec un [exemple de jeu](https://github.com/amontourdeprogrammer/exempledejeu)
- Lundi après midi : Bain de code
- Mardi matin : Forum
- Mardi après midi : Bain de code
- Mercredi matin : Kata sur le code déjà produit
- Mercredi après midi : Bain de code
- Vendredi : Bain de code </dd>

forker le code source → permet de faire bifurquer un repository = Un fork est une copie d’un dépôt. Forker un dépôt vous permet d’expérimenter librement des modifications sans toucher au projet original.
Plus communément, les forks sont utilisés soit pour proposer des modifications sur le projet de quelqu’un d’autre ou pour utiliser le projet de quelqu’un d’autre comme point de départ pour une nouvelle idée.

git diff --patch master

git push -u nomdudossier → -u permet de designer le nom du repository sur lequel pusher =  le nom du dossier → permet ensuite de faire git push tout seul

pull request → mise de la modif sur github puis demande de pull

Create pull request

git show → permet de voir le détail du commit

<dt> Vendredi 8 septembre - 1er journée de suivi </dt>
<dd> - La différence entre le `rebase` et le `merge`, 
- chez /ut7 on préfère le `rebase`
- L'utilisation de `rebase` ou `merge` dépend de l'équipe dans laquelle on est.
- how to do better `ErrorHandling` in `Go`
- En SVG, on a joué avec les propriétés `dasharray` et `dashoffset` dans le css qui va avec un cercle en SVG.
- Pour faire démarrer un cercle à un autre endroit en SVG, on peut utiliser un `transform rotate(xx)` dans le HTML.
- Découverte de `Swift`, on a vu que c'était un langage à typage statique, et qu'il y avait plein de vue différente (le terme revient souvent).
- `Swift` est très différent de `ObjectiveC` au niveau de la syntaxe.
- Surprenant de jouer dans un IDE (XCode) avec un langage à typage statique, ça permet d'avoir des alertes et des erreurs de syntaxe directement, sans exécuter le code.
- Même un éditeur de texte peut afficher des warning et erreurs avec un langage compilé et/ou typé (voir Atom et Go).
- Mieux compris les `callbacks` et les `closure` (fermeture) en JavaScript.
- Une `closure` est une fonction dans une autre fonction qui accède au scope de la fonction parente.
- [message pour @manu ] Quelle différence de prononciation entre `closure` et `clojure` (en anglais).
- Comment enchaîner les tests d'intégrations et les tests unitaires dans un mode de développement piloté par les tests.
- On a vu la pyramide de tests (répartition entre la quantité des tests unitaires et des tests d'intégration)
- JavaScript est mono-thread.
- Existence de ScratchJunior avec des images au lieu du texte, et tactile.
